The tenant of Bakal: The stoves are heating, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing elderly man came out through the door of the RPG Byty customer centre of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He carried under his arm a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and son who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second category apartment 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works with solid fuel", point out on the new contract of his son the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed anyway," he explains, motivated angry and half resigned.
The citizen association of apartments BytyOKD.cz who described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, the date on which a notice will be published explaining the method to be followed to claim.
But the man reacts to this by a gesture of the hand.
"One says that, the other says something else" by frowning.
The Ostrava region became the laboratory for deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not correspond to the market price.
For this reason, Aktualne.cz decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
The waiting room of RPG in Havirovska Street is one of the four in the Ostrava region and it is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "rent 2011", is on the touch screen.
Only one pressure and one paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your number "157" as your number already starts to light up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to find out about the rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people have come to solve common problems like everywhere - demand for repairs, insurance events and others.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving mail with new leases in their mailbox since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers rent increases of 15 to 38 percent.
The special window for new rents has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It's been working for almost a week, so it's still on trial," answers the employee behind the counter after a moment of hesitation when the client presents himself as a journalist.
The deragulation and the former apartments of minors of Bakal are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of parliament and from the region of Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats reported it in a fairly sustained way before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change me a put...n board in the toilets, relieves himself in introduction the man mentioned.
However, according to the employees, it is mainly pensioners who come to make sure that they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a rebate of half of the rent that will be paid to the other lessees who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" window on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by the questions.
"Of the 360 clients who came yesterday, only 40 to 50 came for rent," says the employee at the counter.
And yet RPG is posing individual interviews on rents when needed, both on its website and in the showcases.
If both parties do not agree on the rent, an independent tribunal will make the decision.
"It's not a question of threats, it's just to inform about the unique and legitimate way to act legally," says RPG on its website.
"Here no one will go to court" thinks one of RPG Byty's employees and the man in the street in front of the customer center agrees.
"I have 13,000 pension crowns and I have 5,000 crowns left to eat, I don't have enough to go to court," he says.
The employee suddenly feels uncomfortable.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaoralek in the media asks that no one sign and therefore the people wait," she says.
Rent regulation ends in the Czech Republic with the beginning of 2011 and increases, according to RPG Byty, are an economic necessity.
"And, moreover, the current rents still do not reach the level necessary for the simple maintenance of the housing fund," recalls Pavel Klimes, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, that it is precisely the negligence of the fund for housing that makes the tenant angry is the main reason for the increase of the rent.
However in 5 years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able with rents to invest in apartments 4 billion, in four years from 2011 to 2014 this should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling in front of the upholstered armchairs of the waiting room of Havirosvka Street, repeats however some information indicated in red.
'The increase in rent in 2011 is 15 percent and concerns no less than 31,200 apartments or more than 90 percent of RPG apartments'.
"And it will always be no more than 7.50 Czech crowns per m2 per month," says the screen.
The 38 percent increase concerns only 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In these cases, it is an increase of a really very low sum 19.66 Czech kroner per square metre", adds RPG.
Next year the rent will remain the same for 2600 apartments.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation will not cause a radical but progressive increase over 4 to 8 years.
It adds other commitments: all the money from the increase in rents (see graph) is returned to the apartments in the form of heating savings - new windows and heating.
Those who sign the rent increase agreement have priority.
The nursery school is also part of the offices that have understood the architects.
Brno's Avriopoint administrative building is the new headquarters of Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with everything you need - color walls, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The architectural-project company Arch. Design. whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini nursery business school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, especially of the age to make children, and it was important that women architects and project managers could quickly return to work.
At the same time as reduced employment contracts, nursery school is a bonus offered to its employees by the company Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine work taking care of children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this nursery school and with the support of the management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-school is financed by the European Social Fund through the Human Resources Operational Programme and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding allocations (up to CZK 2.8 mil.) they were able to purchase equipment and appliances and after two years provide qualified personnel and start-up.
After the use of the funding endowment (two years) the company Arch. Design. has the obligation after 3 years to operate the mini nursery school from its own funds.
Project preparation lasted one year and Economy rating helped make the staffing request.
The children are cared for by qualified staff, a nurse and a kindergarten teacher take care of the children all day long. Children can go to kindergarten without age limit but they are over three years old for the most part.
Since it is a "mini nursery school" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more who replace each other.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school without regard to the hierarchical position.
Although there is individual care and education, the nursery school curriculum is comparable to that for pre-school education.
Children don't just play, but quality education is also provided - from the beginning to school preparation, English is taught.
The classroom is equipped not only with imaginative toys and games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can control their child at any time and do not have the stress of being late to pick up the children from a school away from the parents' workplace.
Parents therefore use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that a natural relationship of loyalty is created between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design. has thus registered among the companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and that are friendly to the family and through this program strengthens the marketing of HR.
The bone house fascinates again after 100 years. Take a look in Gaudi's interiors.
The toit resembles the back of a prehistoric saurien, the stairway to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona of architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house was given the nickname Bone House by the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, façade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house unfolds its dream lines, pleasant colours and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation one sees the geometry, the rhythm and the thought order with precision.
In the night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood reproduces in waves the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the eyepiece and the slats.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a rich entrepreneur, first insisted on the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-dwelling house was not conceived by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations were born for a representation apartment of the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade.
For the facade have also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo House began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudi Casa Mila's house and Guell Park in which there are other Gaudi's works.
The locals nicknamed the hot house just after it was finished because of its organic shapes "the Bone House".
Others, in view of the specific window opening mechanism, have called it "the house that yawns".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculpture elements of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems odd.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction directives of the time and did not allow himself to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained a building permit from the city, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the finish the city council was horrified and asked for modifications.
For example, members of the city council were not pleased that the pillars of construction were encroaching on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and obtained satisfaction) for permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent toit terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit itself to the private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi received in addition to new facades a non-traditional roof and two more floors.
Gaudi's play with the light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which is decorated the inner courtyard and with the skylights.
The two-color game gives maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was simply to bet on the principle that the white reflects more than the dark which on the contrary absorbs the rays of the sun.
Casa Battlo House, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and extended the scope of the visits to the common areas and the attic, including the toit terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, pensioners, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discounts.
The sum is still above the entrance price in Gaudi's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic turrets, you must quickly find a comrade among the residents of the building and visit the house completely.
How to choose a mattress and a bed base: women have other criteria than men.
No ostentatious frame, but rather the quality of the surface reserved for the bed, so the mattress and bed base give a real basis for a good bed.
They must of course complement each other harmoniously to please a concrete user.
During the choice several things are decisive: the weight, the height, the age, the state of health as well as the sex of the owner.
The type of interior in which the mattress and spring are to be placed is also important.
A typical example?
For example, in the country house where latex mattresses are not continuously sleeping, they are not suitable because they "warm up" gently.
In addition, they have a higher weight than standard polyurethane mattresses.
It is necessary to return them frequently.
If they do not also have enough ventilation channels in the heart and if they also remain on a solid board, they retain moisture. Mould can also form there.
The habit is also decisive in the choice.
The person who spends the clear of time abroad where very thick mattresses with a softening layer are frequently used, will hardly feel well on a low and hard surface.
"That's how everyone who comes back from NHL complains that they can't sleep there."
"For their tired shoulders, feet and ribs, they needed mattresses with a simmering layer of lazy foam."
"Such mattresses are also recommended for people who suffer from diabetes who have a nervous system disorder which therefore assume poorly "information" of joints and skin," explains Sylva Adamczikova, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That's why a few years ago the mattress with lazy foam conquered the hokeyists as well as other customers.
"Today everything works well, Tempur, the Italian Magnifex but also the Czech Tropico have suitable mattresses, for example.
You don't need to be a NHL guy to be able to enjoy a lazy foam.
This "miracle" simply works.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape according to the heat absorbed or adapts to the heat of your body.
Nothing puts pressure on you and you won't turn around in the night like after a tough game.
You just sleep better.
The lazy foam also works as a protection against squars.
To choose the mattress according to your size, add the length of the feet, about 21/34 cm.
A man and a woman of a size of 180cm therefore need a bed of 210/220cm.
The minimum width for each for a two-seater bed should be 90 cm or a total of 180 cm.
For single beds, singles for example, it is recommended to take at least 120 /140 cm.
It's convenient in case of a visit.
'However it is a simple rule for the width of the bed: when you are lying on the back you should lay hands comfortably with the elbows slightly bent. Helena Prokopova, President of the Association of Bourreliers-mattressiers and decorators who has been dedicated for several years to the problem of a healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture and sign in specialized schools.
For a two-seater bed each needs its own bed base and mattress, so be careful however during the purchase to choose the height of the mattress well.
Otherwise, you will only have to mount the base at different heights and this is not feasible on all bed frames.
The foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, the spring mattresses at least 15 cm, of which count for the layer of shape and ventilation at least three centimeters.
"To the touch or sitting on the mattress you should not feel the springs," warns Helena Prokopova.
Each mattress requires a specific type of spring.
The bed-bed, when the mattress and the bed base are united like siamoese sisters, has nothing to do in the bedrooms.
The mattresses were very bad; it should not be washed, which is commonly done today.
And since during the night we normally sweat from 0.2 to 0.75 l of sweat it is clear that after 5/7 years, the mattress starts to recall a large (and clogged) sieve.
For this purpose the specialists refuse to make a claim over a life of 25 years for a mattress or a lifetime warranty.
But everything to his but.
And for this, an experience advice from the sellers: for a mattress of 120/140cm, give up, for the coating of the mattress, hygiene or washing but instead add a protective mattress that you can easily remove and wash.
And even if nowadays it is common to make coatings with zippers for the whole set, that is to say that after the opening we have two parts (for washing and the size of the washing machine it is very important!) otherwise the handling for the big models (and for one person only) becomes when they are removed a fight between a light weight and a heavy weight in a ring.
Do you have a rigid board in your bed instead of a springboard?
Never!
Maximum for a bed intended for visitors for one night only.
However, equip the board (if there are none) with ventilation holes and use the spring mattress with a minimum height of 15cm with sachet springs (from Germany Taschenfederken) and an aeration layer.
A polyurethane mattress must not be part of a bed of this type.
For single-slatted mattresses with 14/18 slats, latex mattresses or so-called sandwiches (perhaps the combination of latex and coconut) are ideal but it will always be better for you to have a mattress with more slats, 28 and above, where the slats are doubled in the lower part of the kidneys and it is thus possible to regulate the rigidity of them.
For multi-position mattresses, spring mattresses should not be taken because they do not respond to position changes.
Next to the adjustment of the rigidity of the slats we can also install what is called a shoulder cradle.
This is a special connection of the slats that allows to pressure or even tilt the slat so that the shoulder of the sleeper "integrates" well.
For men who have "shoulders as wide as their backs," this is really an important thing.
This thing is already being considered by mattress manufacturers who for "masculines" have begun to use a softening area at shoulder level.
But they also think of women - they offer them a softer surface at the hips again.
For the most difficult customer there are winged or padded bottoms with what is called a multi-force suspension.
Pressure spreads to more points and diinches tension.
But of course, be careful, as soon as you use a bad pillow (large and swollen with air) on good mattresses and springboard, the "plus" disappears.
The basic rule is a simple pillow: the pillow must support the head and its tips must reach only the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can rest.
The recommended size is 50X60 cm that the Scandinavians prefer by example.
When lying on the side, the pillow must level (with the cradle of the shoulder of the spring or the area softened in the mattress) the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses still have something in common with the first ones based on straw and herbs.
Manufacturers still use natural materials or mixtures.
The trend is also with organic mattresses.
The petrole-based raw materials, from which polyurethane is manufactured, are replaced by natural oils, such as soya oil.
Almost all known manufacturers use soy.
"The Bio term for mattresses means that the heart is made from natural products," explains Petr vasicek of Tropico Plus.
Natural materials are also used for mattress coatings; one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can add micro-capsules that develop perfumes from the forest or lavender.
There are differences between men and women.
While the extract of birch plants so that the coating of the mattress absorbs heat and cools the body, "cools" the man, the coatings "heat" the women.
The red pepper extract accelerates blood circulation and is therefore warmer for the weaker sex.
The current favourites?
Mattresses made from cold foam (it has more pores with a disturbed cellular structure so more breathable than the standard polyurethane and has more elasticity.
The combination of different stiffnesses of cold foams gives polyzone mattresses that know exactly where the head, lower back and feet are.
You will pay a quality mattress from 7,000 crowns and more.
Those characterised by their health parameters have less VAT and are taken as instruments for health.
In the Czech Republic, Gumotex reached first place.
Saving for the mattress and the bed base is not simple.
From time to time, two mattresses for the price of a single mattress may be used as part of special actions by manufacturers or producers.
For example, Magniflex offers Duofreeze mattresses with Memory memory foam sewn to cover for 11990 crowns.
We can obviously take the second one for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cell structure and a great thickness was started with Tempur material at a "cosmic" rhythm.
This began as a matter for NASA because astronauts were subjected to enormous load factors at start-up.
The Tempur softens with heat and hardens, on the contrary, with cold.
It adapts perfectly to the warm human body and distributes optimal pressure.
It is ideal for this purpose against sleeping sickness and for an increase in comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses but also for health products, such as special cushions for feet that relieve legs and venous system.
Czech manufacturers use e.g. EucathermC or Twinsaver foam or the same type.
Devices to track people are increasingly being requested by parents who want to watch over their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases as exemple that of the little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a match box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to focus on him something of this type, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smaller ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don't want to be under control'.
"Mobile phones, which can be cut off like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of an attack is highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him or her."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracing devices develop, they (the criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases the criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in an assault not prepared by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an assault.
"The device may be set in such a way that it is in regular emission after a specified period of time".
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned".
"The more expensive devices also have a reclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and ends up lying down without moving," says Cech.
According to him, the so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special prologist.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn in pendants the size of a match box or the smallest telephone sets.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, that is why tests are being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"It will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracing device."
"Or he'll find out after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracing cars.
This is a combination of GPS position acquisition systems (which are commonly used in auto-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
