At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public contest
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, the anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives handcuffed the local entrepreneur and real estate merchant Lubos.
He had tried to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a request for restitution in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a particular candidate.
This one had to pay Lubos G. half a million kroner.
"For the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider trading in the context of a public tender and competition." said for the newspaper Pravo the head of the Public Prosecutor's Office of Plzen Antonie Zelena, knowing that it is forbidden to provide more explanations because the investigation is under way.
The police released the 46-year-old contractor after 24 hours.
To know how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in view of so little official information.
On a question from Pravo, the spokesman for the Lubomira Cerna Land Fund said that the police had actually made an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
"He was a client and in no way an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has as its real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Law on Land" and is set up when several candidates become beneficiaries of rights.
"These persons propose, in the context of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to re-situations which must be settled before the value of the land is announced".
"According to the proposed rights a ranking of the purchasers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights", explained the spokesperson of the Fund.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had registered in the appeal and since he is himself, also, a beneficiary because having bought a large number of rights to restitution, he had offered the candidates on the ground not to participate in the competition.
And he probably cashed in by withdrawing.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terrains).
He appeared in the case of the former head of the FdT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted in criminal proceedings for editing land for which the decision to set up a building had already been published.
For example, Lubos G. had obtained land intended for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the access artery to the Borske Pole industrial zone was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was forced to accept because otherwise it risked endangering the construction by blocking the land.
