A dirty vote
No one expected to have perfect general elections in Haiti on November 28.
But it was far worse than the outsiders who wanted to help the disaster-stricken and fearful country.
Poll boxes and a new ballot were introduced, ballots were dispersed in the gutter, polling stations were ransacked and intimidation was reported.
The polling stations opened late in the evening.
Many Haitians, including many who were displaced as a result of the January earthquake, were wandering around to find where to vote.
Some of them ended up giving up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several alleged favourites, denounced the fraud and called for the annulment of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded throughout the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the senior official in Haiti of the United Nations, considers the event as "a fairly good election in many respects".
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that they “did not believe that such irregularities, however serious they may be, had necessarily invalidated the process”.
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are indebted to René Préval, unpopular outgoing president, and his candidate, Jude Célestin, must announce the preliminary results on 7 December.
The second round is scheduled for January.
All hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rap musician, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial call for the vote to be declared void.
But there may be problems if Mr. Célestin, who has little or no visible support among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second round, reaches the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors still living in tents, there was concern that participation would be possible.
In this case, many Haitians wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of disorganization.
Nearly 250,000 identity cards, necessary for voting, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The stakes are important.
Donors see the election of a legitimate people's government as an important step in Haiti's reconstruction.
And so, it's clear, Haitians do it themselves.
