In the weeks after she suddenly became a widow, Cristina Fernández, president of Argentina, received a wave of sympathy from the public which improved her approval rate by 20 points, to more than 50%; this is her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
However, turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on Mrs Fernández's choice, apparently in mourning, that she would abandon or not the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain confused.
Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy, even after his wife succeeded him as president, was used to preparing budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the first couple to spend the extra income at will.
Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
