Sport and fraud of the law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape punishment.
The expulsion in principle by two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match of 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League made a lot of ink on the anti-sportive character of such behavior and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before they finished the game (which their team was already clearly winning), both players deliberately wasted time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually be the leader of its group, the two players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next match of the barrage game against Auxerre and will be able to pass without boxes in the next phase.
Finally, UEFA's Disciplinary Committee sanctioned with two games the team's coach, José Mourinho and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the case was due to the fact that this involved a team from Real Madrid's entity (who in his anthem displays nobility and honour and who on past occasions sentenced his players to a fine for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour, which is not expressly prohibited by the regulation, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether such actions commit fraud by law; for, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that includes the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, i.e. there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that are alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the player's team from profiting in an unfair way from the opposite team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the arbitrator.
They were waiting and willingly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders obtain from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put the rival in a position of disadvantage and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And that's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Of course the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without boxes that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, as the team could be eliminated all of a sudden and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cartons, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladders, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which still forms part of the strategic decision-making that favours the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the penalty (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted themselves to it.
They made a strategic decision without playing the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and the fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, appears because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was transmitted to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
